{
  "texts": [
    "That is, the blockchain can most easily interact with information on the chain, leaving little room to consider issues such as fact-checking or moral alignment.",
    "Oftentimes, to develop mechanisms that seek to assist with LLM toxicity or factuality, oracles are used to bridge this gap [34,31].",
    "Serving as mediators between chains and online sources, oracles are trusted parties that deliver information through a variety of protocols and frameworks.",
    "However, introducing a trusted party into an otherwise trustless system has been a long-standing weak point in this solution [76].",
    "Exploring non-oracle-based options for ground truth solu-tions, or toxicity checks, would greatly enhance the security guarantees of blockchain within LLMs."
  ]
}